iour, activist movements, climate policy, and immigrant retention. While the theoretical perspectives and kinds of questions asked vary greatly, as a whole they demonstrate how the "art of comparing" is an important strategy for understanding Canadian identity politics, political mobilization, political institutions, and public policy. Ultimately, this book establishes how adopting a more systematic comparative outlook is essential -- not only to revitalize the study of Canadian politics but also to achieve a more nuanced understanding of Canada as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical sciencezCanadaxComparative method. 0aPolitical sciencezCanadaxMethodology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aBilodeau, Antoine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoychuk, Gerard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBéland, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodbout, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Kristin R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraefe, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoule, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLachapelle, Erick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLecours, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahon, Rianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrsini, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapillon, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct